Notes: Some wolves or packs will sometimes follow the caribou herds when prey density in territory is low (mean of 11% of packs annually migrated with caribou)
Mass_Details: From Fish and Wildlife personal communications, the mean of the average adult male (96kg) and the average adult female (76kg)
Prey_Notes: Migratory and thus caribou availability can change drastically at different times of year and for different packs.  Caribou are on their spring migration (and travelling through the study area) during this study period. May-June they calve in the northern part of the study area. After calving move to the eastern half of the study area then late Oct/Nov they migrate to the south portion of the study area and during winter about half of the herd is further south than the study area (ie half the herd spends winter in the southern portion of the study area).

Mass_Details: From Franzmann et al. 1978 and Hayes et al. 1991, the mean of the average adult male (454kg) and the average adult female (400kg)
Prey_Notes: 13% of cows have twins (ie this pop is below the average moose twinning rate of 33% in the rest of north america). "Moose typically use relatively high elevations during summer and autumn and move to lowland riparian areas for winter."

Prey_Notes: High habitat overlap with wolves. Individual encounter rate of 0.69 (highest od any prey) and group encounter of 0.38 (second highest encounter). Mean herd size of 10.3. Southern half of Bow Valley is an important wintering area for elk. "rarely defend themselves actively (Carbyn 1974), but frequently seek refuge in deep water". May be more detectable to wolves since they are larger, in larger herds, and more frequently occupy more open areas. Flee from wolves.
